Mistake 3: Not Updating the Counter Variable
If the counter variable is not updated inside the loop, it may result in an infinite loop.

**Error Example:**

```js
let a = 1;
let counter = 1;
while (counter < 3) {
    a = a + 1;
    console.log(a);
}
console.log("End");
```

* **Fix**: Always update the counter variable to prevent an infinite loop.

code_playground.code:
// BUG: counter is never updated — this would loop forever.
// We limit to 5 iterations here just to show the problem safely.
let a = 1;
let counter = 1;
let iterations = 0;
while (counter < 3) {
    a = a + 1;
    console.log("a is now:", a, "| counter is still:", counter);
    iterations++;
    if (iterations >= 5) {
        console.log("Stopped early — counter never changed, loop would never end!");
        break;
    }
}
// console.log("End") would never be reached without the break above.

// FIX: counter is updated inside the loop.
let a = 1;
let counter = 1;
while (counter < 3) {
    a = a + 1;
    console.log("a is now:", a, "| counter is:", counter);
    counter = counter + 1; // <-- the fix
}
console.log("End");
